{"ts": "2026-07-19T03:36:01.065Z", "seq": 28, "kind": "consideration", "summary": "THE ERASURE AUDIT TRAIL IS DESTRUCTIBLE -- refutes the v4 design of record. dev/design/0.8.20-erasure-and-h-end-state-v4.md section 3.6 asserts excise_source_audit 'retains source_id PERMANENTLY (:6479) -- by design; that is the audit trail', and plan-0.8.20.md section 8 repeats it as the justification for the non-PII source_id rule. VERIFIED FALSE at 4ca70ba6: the audit row is written into operational_mutations (engine lib.rs:6479), and enforce_provenance_retention (:10070) sweeps THAT SAME TABLE cap-first, oldest-id-first, with NO COLLECTION FILTER (:10083-10089: DELETE FROM operational_mutations WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM operational_mutations ORDER BY id LIMIT ?1)). Erasure audit rows are swept like any other op-store row. TWO CONSEQUENCES: (1) ACCOUNTABILITY GAP -- demonstrating THAT an erasure occurred is a distinct obligation from performing it; a retention sweep can silently destroy the proof. (2) COLLISION WITH WORK ITEM 9 -- excise_collection_record operates on the op-store, the SAME table the audit rows live in, so the erasure record and the payloads being erased share one retention pool. The non-PII source_id rule STILL STANDS (an unswept audit row may still hold it) but its stated rationale is argued from a false premise and must be corrected. RECOMMENDED (HITL, decision owed): exempt the erasure-audit collection from enforce_provenance_retention by filtering the sweep by collection, and state the audit-durability guarantee explicitly. This is a RETENTION-POLICY change, not a pure defect repair, hence HITL-gated.", "cx": "TC-15", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "OPEN", "refs": ["file:dev/design/0.8.20-slice0-erasure-design.md#2", "seq:24"]}

